@node Intro "Introduction"

If you're like me, you like to show off your Amiga every time you have a chance. One of my
ways to do this, is to constantly change the appearance of my Workbench. That would be
really easy if the only thing I had to do was change the WBPattern prefs. And for many
people, it is that easy. If you're one of them, stop reading right now. Go away.

However, if you think that you need to change more than the WBPattern, Moods might be for
you.
When I change the appearance of my WB, I change the whole thing. The font and its colors,
the Beep-sound, maybe the screenmode and so on. This is IMHO too much work, and thats
why I decided to make Moods. With Moods, you can simply make an archive of the current
system preferences, ready to be recalled when you need/want it. This allows you to have
a lot of different "feels" on your WB, or, as I call them, "moods". I have several moods -
a "Boring"-mood, that shows a normal, boring workbench. A "UNIX"-mood, that looks like
a normal, boring UNIX terminal ;). A "Tolkien" mood that has a cool Tolkien-inspired
background and matching fonts, and a Win95_I_Think_Not mood with a (self-produced)
raytraced background. Each time I get a new cool picture I can use as a background,
a new mood is born. And it's really easy to switch between them, all thanks to Moods.

Of course, if there is a vital feature you want added to Moods, feel free to contact me,
after reading the To Do part of this document. :)
@endnode

@node Req "Requirements"
You need the following on your Amiga for this program to be usable:

   À AmigaDOS v2.1 (V38) or later
   À reqtools.library, at least V38
   À Lha installed somewhere in your path
   À The Commodore standard installer, also in your path.
   À A few kB of free disk space..:)

Moods has been tested on the CyberGFx gfx-card emulations system, and it works
like a dream.
@endnode

