@node Inst "Installing Moods"

                              How to install Moods

   À  After unpacking the archive (preferably to RAM:), locate the Moods
      drawer, open it, and double click on the icon named "Install Moods".
      This will start up the Commodore (R.I.P.) Installer utility, which
      you must have installed somewhere in your path.
   À  The installer window will pop up. Choose if you want to log the actions
      of the installer, then press the Proceed button.
   À  Read the three annoying messages, pressing Proceed as you go along.
   À  Choose where to put the Moods directory. Although the installer defaults
      to SYS:, SYS:Tools/ might be a better place for it. Or SYS:Utilities.
      Anyway, there's a requester, so you decide. Press Proceed to go on.
   À  The installer will inform you that it will create some enviroment-
      variables. The program needs these to work properly, so be a good boy
      and press Proceed.
   À  Next, it informs you that it copies the Moods-program to your Prefs-
      directory. This way, you can pop into that dir and select a Mood from
      this program directly.
   À  Now it copies the Setup program to the Moods directory. Just let it.
   À  Now it will tell you that it's done, and also that you should read
      this file. It's good advice, but it's up to you.

The program is now properly installed. Your next logical step would be to use
the Setup-program to create some moods, as the Moods-program needs these things
to work. :)
@endnode

@node Using "How to use the programs"

The Moods distrubition consists of two programs: Moods and Setup. Moods is
installed in your SYS:Prefs directory, and Setup in the Moods-directory that
was created during the installation process.

How to use Setup:
   Setup is the program in which you make the actual "moods". What you do is
   this:
      À Set all the prefs-files as you want them. Configure backgrounds,
        pointers, system sounds and so on.
      À Start up Setup. If this is your first time, it should open a window
        with an empty listview and some gadgets. If not, see the
        Troubleshooting section.
      À Click on the Add-button. This will make a new mood for you. Now you
        edit the name of the mood, and click the Save-gadget.
        PLEASE make sure that the name of the mood is a legal AmigaDOS
        filename, as the archive of the mood will be called <name>.lha.
      À Now configure your system again, each time adding a mood and saving
        it.
      À To delete a mood, select it in the listview and press Delete.
        If will ask you if you're really sure. Reply.
      À If you want to set the system to a specific mood, select it and click
        the Set To button.
      À Whenever you click the closegadget of the window, it will save the
        current moodlist and exit.

How to use Moods:
   The purpose of Moods is simple; To select the mood of your Workbench.
      À Double-click on the Moods-icon. If, and only if, you have any
        moods installed on your system, a window will pop up, with a
        listview containing the moods, and two gadgets - OK and Cancel.
      À Select the mood you want in the listview, and click OK. The
        program will set your system as it was when you saved the mood,
        and then exit.
      À If you want to chicken out, press Cancel or the close gadget.


NOTES:
   1) Currently, when you make a mood, Setup only grabs the files in
      ENV:Sys/ - this is supposed to be changed, hopefully soon, so that
      you can select which files to include yourself.
   2) When you make a new mood, the program does NOT check if the name
      is a legal AmigaDOS filename (yet). Please make sure that it is, or
      bad things may happen.
@endnode

@node OhNo "Troubleshooting"
Damn, this shouldn't happen...But nobody's perfect..

   Q When I try to start either of the programs, it tells me something about
     enviroment variables? WTF?

   A It needs the local/global variable MoodsPath set to the directory that
     was created during the installation process. If this enviroment-variable
     doesn't exist, the program can't find its data files. Use the SetEnv
     command to make a new variable, and copy it to ENVARC: as well, so that
     it'll survive a reboot.

   Q I tried to start either of the programs, and my HD gave a freak noise,
     then died. My monitor fell down, and the CPU card burned. Then the
     keyboard rotted, my mouse melted, and I broke a leg.

   A Refer to the "Legal" section. ;)

   Q How come the Moods program won't start?

   A You need to define some moods using the Setup program first.

   Q Yeah, right. I've done that already.

   A Perhaps you didn't press the "Save"-button after adding it?

   Q Oh, yeah, my fault.

   A I knew that.

   Q I try to start either program, but it just exits right away!

   A I think you have one of two possible problems:

      1) Your Workbench/Kickstart is too old.
      2) You do not have enough memory.

   Q The program runs too fast on my Workbench!

   A That's because I don't use MUI. It's a feature.
@endnode

